<body class="ignore-math"><article class="exercise exercise-like"><div class="introduction"><p>We've integrated the trigonometric functions <span class="process-math">\(\sin(x){}\text{,}\)</span> <span class="process-math">\(\cos(x){}\text{,}\)</span> <span class="process-math">\(\tan(x){}\text{,}\)</span> and <span class="process-math">\(\cot(x){}\text{.}\)</span> Now we will deal with secant and cosecant.</p></div>
<article class="task exercise-like"><h4 class="heading"><span class="codenumber">(a)</span></h4>
<p>Consider the following "trick",</p>
<div class="displaymath process-math" data-contains-math-knowls="">
\begin{equation*}
\int\sec(x)\dx{x}=\int\sec(x)\frac{\sec(x)+\tan(x){}}{\tan(x)+\sec(x){}}\dx{x}=\int\frac{\sec^2(x)+\sec(x)\tan(x)}{\tan(x)+\sec(x)}\dx{x}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p class="continuation">Do you recognize a substitution that can be used?  Use this to integrate <span class="process-math">\(\sec(x)\dx{x}{}\text{.}\)</span></p></article><article class="task exercise-like"><h4 class="heading"><span class="codenumber">(b)</span></h4>
<p>Use a similar trick to compute <span class="process-math">\(\int\csc(x)\dx{x}{}\text{.}\)</span></p></article></article></body>
</html>
